I’ve been pretty quiet lately on the mom front but it’s mostly because Ive been overwhelmed. Eliaz turned 6 last week and with it has come new obstacles. But moments like today remind me that all the chaos and work we do is for this, this small moment. I fought through many store trips with a screaming and frustrated child. There were times I was scared to even take Eliaz to any store because he wanted to run, spin or just take all of anything he wanted. Just waiting in line can be a struggle with a child on the spectrum. So many moments that other parents don’t even think twice about, I have planned, thought out, pictured and prepped myself mentally and emotionally to deal with. But it has made me stronger and graceful in many ways. Eliaz is truly the light of my life and has given me more than he’ll ever know. #autismawareness #autismmom #nonverbalautism

Keith Harring at the broad. 
Before social media I’d come across artist and completely immerse myself into finding out all I could about them. Harring was one of those artist. Id geek out anytime I’d see “dancing men” figures being used before it became over commercialized. It spoke to adult me and young me and I had great appreciation for Keith’s work, even more so when I became a mother. 
I had Keith’s art all over the boys room when they were younger and in 2020 even styled our Christmas tree with Keith art because it was the year the boys dad and I separated and I felt like we visually needed that big red heart energy. 
Everything means something in my life, every piece in my home, when I dress, I am so intentional about the world around me. This exhibition reminded me how special Keith’s work is, the small details that turn out to all come together to create a bigger picture. 🫶🏻

Christmas looked different this year but in the best way✨ navigating through the holidays when you have to coparent isn’t easy, but at the end of the day it’s all about the boys. As much as I may make things look effortless, there is in fact a lot of effort and tears involved. I’m so lucky to have so many people in my corner. People who listen to me, validate me, see me and try to make my days a little easier even if it’s just a coffee delivery. None of it goes unnoticed! Even Ed (my nail tech)had me crying on Xmas eve because he made space for me on his day off. In slide 5 you can see when we found out that we were blessed with a suite to the game from my fairy godmother. All in all, the boys had such a special day and it’s really true when they say “it takes a village”. Baby I’m so thankful for my village, team, squad, soulmates, what ever you wanna call it!
